HEADWORD: Pharisee
<hw>Phar"i*see</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧r"⟦icr⟧*s⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>Pharisaeus</ets>, Gr. <grk>Farisai^os</grk>, from Heb.
<ets>p⟦amac⟧rash</ets> to separate.]</ety> <def>One of a sect or party
among the Jews, noted for a strict and formal observance of rites and
ceremonies and of the traditions of the elders, and whose pretensions to
superior sanctity led them to separate themselves from the other
Jews.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phariseeism</ent>⟦br⟧
